Indonesia: dengue hemorrhagic fever data as of mid-July 2003
------------------------------------------------------------
[This report has been edited to bring it into line with standard
ProMED-mail format. - Mod.CP]
During 2003 up to the middle of July there have been 18 797 dengue
fever/dengue hemorrhagic fever (DF/DHF) cases reported from 30 provinces
and 188 districts in Indonesia, with 256 fatal cases (case fatality rate
(CFR) = 1.4 per cent). With a total population of 210 million the incidence
is 8.80 [per 10 000] DHF cases reported from hospitals. Indonesian
hospitals have relied on clinical diagnostics, employing standard World
Health Organization (WHO) criteria. Differential diagnosis between DF and
DHF was based on plasma leakage with the indicator haematocrit (20 per cent
increasing or down) and a thrombocyte count below 100 000/mm3. Only a few
of those cases were tested using serological IgM, IgG and hemagglutination
inhibition tests.
DF/DHF cases have been reported for almost 35 years in Indonesia. The
endemic provinces are Jakarta (the capitol ciy), South Sumatera, East Java,
West and East Kalimanatan, South and North Sulawesi with incidences ranging
from 20 to 70 [per 10 000].
Indonesia has a national DHF control program which includes surveillance
and epidemiology, vector control (mosquito and larvae), health education,
case management, inter-sectoral partnership and community participation,
training, and research.
--
Dr Rita Kusriastuti
Head of Sub Directorate Arbovirosis
MOH Indonesia
JAKARTA
