Source: The Manila Times, Thu 7 Aug 2003 [edited]
<http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2003/aug/07/prov/20030807pro1.html>

Philipinnes: dengue ravages La Union & Cordillera
-------------------------------------------------
SAN FERNANDO CITY: La Union health authorities have raised the alarm about
the rapid increase in the number of dengue cases in the province, where 5
people have already died. The office of the Department of Health in the
Cordillera Administrative Region (DOH-CAR) also reported an alarming
increase in the CAR, from 62 dengue cases in 2002 to 353 this year with one
death. This is a fivefold increase in [dengue] cases, Elnoria Bugnoses of
the Regional Epidemiology Surveillance Unit told The Times.
This developed as Dr Jose Ostrea, chief of the La Union provincial health
office, reported that a total of 142 dengue patients had sought treatment
in various government and private hospitals since January. Most of the
patients were admitted to the hospitals at the start of the rainy season,
Ostrea said. The 5 reported dead from dengue were residents of this capital
city as well as the towns of Agoo, Bagulin, Aringay, and Naguilian. Of the
total of 142 cases, the capital city of San Fernando, was on top with 36,
followed by Aringay with 23, Bauang 13, San Juan 11, and Bacnotan 10. The
remaining 16 towns in the province have reported at least one dengue case
each, Ostrea said. Reports are that Bacnotan has more than the reported 10
dengue cases.
Meanwhile, a separate report by Emily Laroya, a nurse at the San Fernando
health office, confirmed that this city has the highest number of dengue
cases at 36 as of Wednesday. Laroya said the number includes the 5
additional patients from Barangays Bato and Saoay, who sought treatment in
the hospitals here. She added that city officials have ordered the
intensification of fogging operations, particularly in barangays hardest
hit by the disease.
In the Cordillera, Bugnosen said Ifugao has the highest number of cases
with 132, followed by Baguio with 94, Benguet 65, Mt Province 42, and
Kalinga 3.
There were no reported cases in the two other CAR provinces, Abra and
Apayao, Bugnosen said. The sharp increase in cases reflects the dengue
outbreak in Virac, Ifugao, and Itogon, Benguet.
[byline: William Garcia Jr and Laarni Ilagan]
