Caribbean Region: decrease in prevalence of Dengue/DHF
------------------------------------------------------
During epidemiological weeks 14 to 26, 2003, 391 cases of dengue fever and
10 cases of dengue haemorrhagic fever (DHF) were reported to CAREC,
compared to 1498 cases of dengue fever and 34 cases of DHF in the
corresponding period last year. This fourfold decrease is likely to be due
to the delayed onset of the rainy season in 2003. During the period under
review 97 per cent of the dengue fever cases were reported from 4
countries, Barbados, Guyana, Suriname, and Trinidad and Tobago.
During the period under review dengue virus type 2 was reported from
Suriname. During the first 13 weeks of 2003, dengue virus type 3 was also
reported from 3 countries, Anguilla, Barbados, and St. Vincent and the
Grenadines.
Since the rainy season has recently commenced CAREC recommends that all
countries should establish or re-establish a dengue fever/DHF outbreak
contingency plan, which should include: preparedness regarding clinical
case management; immediate adulticidal treatments in the vicinity of the
residence of confirmed patients, and the place of work etc, as well as in
other locations where persons are experiencing dengue-like symptoms;
efforts should be made in source reduction activities by householders and
communities, spearheaded by public health authorities. Communities and
inter-sectoral groups should help with organized clean-ups to reduce
sources of mosquito breeding; households with people experiencing febrile
illness should utilize repellents and intra-domiciliary (space) sprays for
personal protection against mosquito bites. Individuals and families could
benefit from such activity; health promotion and education should be used
strategically to encourage communities in this fight against the vector;
inter-sectoral collaboration between the Ministry of Health and Public
Utilities to ensure the availability of water and acceptable levels of
environmental sanitation.
Given that West Nile Virus is present in many eastern states of the USA, it
is likely to be introduced into many Caribbean countries in the near
future. A dengue fever/DHF outbreak contingency plan would also assist in
the prevention and control of West Nile infection. [This report also
includes a table giving cumulative data for dengue/DHF cases by country up
to the end of June 2003; a significant aspect being a high frequency of DHF
in Trinidad and Tobago.]
